Variable Annuity Introduction

A variable annuity, like many other insurance products, is a contract between a policyholder and an insurance company, under which the policyholder agrees to make either a single purchase payment or a series of purchase payments. And the policyholder will receive a lump sum payment, annuitize accumulated asset base or begin taking regular withdrawals from sub-accounts. The premiums, or purchase payments from the policyholder are invested in a sub-account and the performance of this sub-account is linked in proportion to the ???uctuation of equity index or equity fund in which it invests. For this reason, variable annuities can also be called equity-linked insurance.

There are a wide range of variable annuity products on the market, our project is focused on the Guaranteed Minimum Death Benefit (GMDB). The GMDB is derived from some more basic insurance product such as traditional whole life insurance. Under traditional whole life insurance, a policyholder pays premium periodically (monthly, quarterly, semiannually, or annually), and a pre-determined death benefit goes to his beneficiary at the time of his death. The difference between GMDB and a traditional whole life insurance is that, for GMDB, the death benefit is generally equal to the greater of (a) a fixed amount specified on the contract or (b) premium payments invested in the market minus any prior withdrawals. The GMDB is attractive to both insurers and policyholders. The insurers could capture more capital gains in the stock market and the policyholders will keep up with the market to know their families will be protected against economic loss in the event of an untimely death.

To price the GMDB product, we need to consider the three sources of risk, decrement risk, investment risk and discount rate risk. We illustrate how the three sources of risk affect the premium on the graph below:

Variable Annuity Sources of Risks

At time zero, there is a group of policyholders. The insurance company will charge the premiums and invest the money into a sub-account which linked to a stock. As we move forward, the number of policyholders will decrease. We will need to evaluate the decrement risk and simulate the number of remaining policyholders each year. Also, as the policyholders die, we need to take money out of the account to pay the death benefit while the remaining amount will stay in the account. Secondly, we need to simulate the stock performance based on the investment mode. We denote “R” as the performance of the underlying stock on the graph, which is also the performance of the account. Lastly, we need to model the discount rate, denoted by “r”, to discount back the future cash flow. With the discount rate model, the insurance company can calculate the account value at each point on the timeline. Therefore, the insurers will be able to apply different premium principle to model the premium they need to charge to individual policyholders.

Models: Mortality Decrement

In this project, we primarily concern about the risk of mortality under this source of risk. Let’s define (x) as a life age at x, \(T_{(x)}\) as the remaining life time random variable of (x), and \(\mathbb{P}(T_{(x)}>t)\)as the probability that a life (x) survive and extra t years, which can also be denoted by \(_{t}p_{x}\). To simulate the future life time of a policyholder, we need the continuous survival function. Once we have the continuous survival function, we could get the CDF and PDF. Then, we could apply the methods, such as inverse transformation and Accept-Reject. We will use a Life table to estimate the survival function. Below is a sample of Life Table:

x \(l_{x}\) \(d_{x}\)
0 100000 637
1 99363 45
2 99318 28

\(l_x\) is the number of survivors at age x, and \(d_x\) is the number of deaths during age x. The formula for the estimator for integral ages is \(\widehat{_{t}p_x} = \frac{l_{x+t}}{l_x}\). Since Life Table is a discretized continuous model, we could use UDD assumption for fractional ages, which is to apply linear interpolation for fractional ages. Finally, we have a continuous survival model for any fractional age.

Model: Equity Investment Return

The equity investment return can be modeled in many different ways. First we need some period of historical stock performance data, which we can use to estimate the parameters and predict future return of that particular stock. Typically, Brownian Motion (both arithmetic and geometric) and time series forecasting methods (ARIMA, auto-regressive) are ways to help achieve this goal. In this project, we used geometric Brownian motion to stimulate future stock prices; however, we hope to complete the inventory in the future.

A geometric Brownian motion is a continuous stochastic process in which the logarithm of the randomly varying quantity follows a Brownian motion with drift. (from Wikipedia) It satisfies the following stochastic differential equation.

\[\frac{dS_t}{S_t}=\mu dt+\sigma dW_t\]

\(\mu\) represents the percentage drift and \(\sigma\) represents the percentage volatility. This basically means that after infinitesimal time \(dt\), the price \(dS_t\) equals to \(S_t\) times the drift and volatility factor. Solving this equation , we get:

\[\frac{S_t}{S_0} \sim lgnorm(\mu-\frac{1}{2}\sigma^2,\sigma)\] In our case, \(S_0\) denotes the last stock closing price of the training data and \(S_t\) denotes the predicted stock closing price after t periods. The solution of the SDE indicates the \(\frac{S_t}{S_0}\) follows a log-normal distribution.

Then we proceed to estimate the \(\mu\) and \(\sigma\) from historical data using maximum likelihood estimation (MLE). To ache hive this, we used fitdistr function from the fitdistributionplus package. After that we can use the known parameters to stimulate the stock paths.

The code for this model is structured into four functions, all of which has their own functionality. The first function is risk.clean.data. This function acquires data through getSymbols function in the quantmod package and make sure it is ready for analysis. The Second function is called risk.calibrate. This function estimates the log-normal parameters. The third function is risk.predict. By utilizing previous parameters and random number generating method(rnorm), we created a matrix containing multiple predicted stock path values. The fourth part is a plotting function called risk.plot. This function helps to visualize the stock paths by shading the confidence intervals and plotting the median and mean of the stock paths.

Model: (Risk-free) Discount Rate

Just like the Equity Investment Return, there are a lot of models which we can utilize to predict future interest rate risk. Vasicek, Black-Derman-Toy, and Cox-Ingersoll-Ross are all very good models that can help us predict the future projection of interest rates. However, again, due to time constraints, we only built one interest rate model featuring the classic Vasicek model.

Vasicek Short Rate Model is a mathematical model describing the evolution of interest rates. (from Wikipedia) The model specifies the instantaneous interest rate follows stochastic differential equation shown below:

\[dr_t=a(b-r_t)dt+\sigma dW_t\]

solving the SDE, we can get that \(\mathbb{E}[r_t]=r_0e^{-at}+b(1-e^{-at}), \space \space Var[r_t] = \frac{\sigma^2}{2a}(1-e^{-2at})\)

Similar to the simulations of stock paths, we used the same methodologies. The code can be break down into the following parts: disc.clean.data, disc.calibrate, disc.predict, disc.simulate.vasicek.helper, disc.simulate.vasicek,disc.predict.vasicek, disc.predict.vasicek.ZCBondPrice, disc.predict.vasicek.YieldCurve, and disc.plot.

disc.clean.data is used to clean data pulled from getSymbol for following analysis.

disc.calibrate is used to calibrate a model using data provided.

disc.calibrate.vasicek is used to calibrates the Vasicek model using the maximum likelihood estimator. Details about the maximum likelihood estimator are at the link below.

disc.predict is used to predict future discount factor based on the fitted model

disc.simulate.vasicek.helper is a helper function that calculates the next rate based on the discretization of the Vasicek model.

disc.simulate.vasicek is used to generate a single short rate simulation using the Vasicek model.

disc.predict.vasicek is used to generate several short rate simulations using the Vasicek model.

disc.simulate.vasicek,disc.predict.vasicek is used to calculate the zero coupon bond price.

disc.plot is used to plot historic data and predictions.

###Random number generator### In our project, we constructed a random number generator that based on the knowledge we gained this class. Our random number generator can recognize three types of methods users intend to use: inverse CDF, accept-reject and Metropolis-Hasting Sampling, with different input parameters.

  • The inverse CDF generator takes a sample size of n and an inverse CDF function, and then returns a vector of identical independent distributed sample of length n.

  • The accept-reject generator takes a sample size of n, three functions of target and proposal distribution (dtarget, dproposal and rproposal) and a normalizeing constant. The dtarget function is the density function of target distribution. The dproposal function is the density function of proposal distribution. The rproposal function is the random number generator of proposal distribution. The normalizing constant, C, is defaulted “auto”. If C’s value is auto, another function that calculate the value of normalizing constant is called. The accept-reject generator returns a list consisting of the vector of generated identical independent distributed sample and the number of rejections before reaching the sample size desired.

  • Similar to accept-reject method, the Metropolis-Hasting generator takes number of sample size, three functions of target and proposal distribution and an additional parameter: x.init, the initial point of the chain. X.int is defaulted as NA. If it’s not specified, rproposal(n, param) must have default param value. The Metropolis-Hasting generator generates a list consisting of a vector of identical independent distributed sample of length n and the number of rejections before reaching the sample size.

The purpose of random number generator in our project is to generate random sample for decrement, investment and discount rate. The life table used in decrement section fellows a certain discrete distribution. We generated a uniform distribution from zero to one and use the inverse CDF method to produce identical independent distributed sample of people’s life span from the life table. As for accept-reject method and Metropolis-Hasting sampler, we use it to produce identical independent distributed sample for Vicsek model and Brownian motion, which were discussed in the investment and discount rate section. The sample code is applied to the function decrement.predict and is shown below:

x <- STAT428.random.number.1D(n = n*N,

###Bootstrap### + Parametric Bootstrap Defition and Methodology Generally, the parametric bootstrap is a technique to draw new observations from a fitted parametric model. For linear regression: Suppose \(y_1, y_2, ...., y_n\) are identically and independently drawn from a p.d.f \(f(y; x,\beta)\), which depends on unknown parameters \(\beta\). Let \(\hat{\beta}\) be an estimate of \(\beta\) using least square regression. The parametric bootstrap draws replicates of a statistic T by simulating datasets of size n from the p.d.f \(f(y; x,\hat{\beta})\), each time computing a replicate \(\hat{T}\). Specifically, T can be new estimation for later functions.

In our project, bootstrap method is used on generating errors of maximum likelihood parameter estimate mu and sigma of the Geometric Brownian Motion which applied to investment rate and discount rate.

  • Bootstrap Function Usage The sample code is shown below:
inv.calibrate <- function (hist.data, model) {
  if(model=="GBM"){
    n <- nrow(hist.data) #sample size
    return <- numeric(n) #storage for replicates
    for(i in 1:n-1){
      return[i] <- as.numeric(hist.data[i+1])/as.numeric(hist.data[i])
    }
    return <- return[-which(return == 0)]
    param <- as.numeric(fitdistrplus::fitdist(return, distr = "lnorm", method = "mle")$estimate)
    return(param)
  }
}
risk.calibrate <- function (data, model = "GBM"){
  if(model=='GBM'){
    n <- nrow(data) #sample size
    return <- numeric(n) #storage for replicates
    for(i in 1:n-1){
      return[i] <- as.numeric(data[i+1])/as.numeric(data[i])
    }
    return <- return[-which(return == 0)]
    param <- as.numeric(fitdistrplus::fitdist(return, distr = 'lnorm', method = 'mle')$estimate)
    return(param)
  }
}
